Title: Adapt Linux Trace Toolkit (LTT) Visualization Tool
Description:
Investigate the use of the LTT Visualization Tool and its input file format(s). The goal is to use it to display traces from the RTEMS Capture Engine. Your goal is to get it to display an arbitrary timeline.

This will provide us with the definition of the input files so the RTEMS Capture Engine's output can be visualized using the LTT Visualization Tool.

This Wiki entry will contain any additional details:

http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Adapt_Linux_Trace_Toolkit_.28LTT.29_Visualization_Took

Title: Create RTEMS Project Wiki Page for ESA GAIA Mission
Description: The RTEMS Project has a number of flyers at http://www.rtems.org/flyers.html which provide some details on various projects which have used RTEMS.  Each of these flyers is based upon a Wiki page about that project with the same or similar text and pictures.  This task consists of preparing a wiki page on an RTEMS application which consists of approximately one to two pages of text plus 2 or more nice pictures or figures about the project and a few URLs of reference for more details.  The information on the flyers is based on this and is presented in a very uniform manner. The Wiki page is easier to edit and review collaboratively. We will create the flyer from the information on the Wiki page you create. Most of the information you need should be available from public sources on the Internet. When you take this task you may be given an email address of a contact for that project to obtain information from.  The wiki page you will create is for the ESA GAIA Mission. More details about this project and some hints for searching and creating content may be found at http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Info_for_flyers_for_various_projects_using_RTEMS

Title: Test Coverage Report Improvements #1
Description:
This task consists of modifying the existing Bourne shell script that generates the primary table of results per target. An example of this can be found in the erc32 coverage results at http://www.rtems.org/ftp/pub/rtems/people/joel/coverage/erc32.html#OsPD.

This is a task which is a step in a multiple step project.

Break out the current one page per target with a section per test configuration with a table into separate pages. The top level table will consist only of links to a set of pages per test configuration. The new pages will consist of the table. The plotted data of multiple test configurations should be removed. Instead each "per test configuration" page should include a plot of the data ONLY for that configuration.

The scripts are in the rtems-testing git module. You will need to be familiar with git and Bourne Shell programming. Ask for sample data to use when working on this task. You will not need to run our test suite -- just generate reports based on their output.

For more details, see http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Test_Coverage_Report_Improvements

Title: MOBI Format for User Documentation
Description:
t would be nice to offer the RTEMS Document Set in an ebook format so it is available in a suitable format for cell phones, eReaders, PDAs, etc. This project is to evaluate how various eBbook formats can be produced using our Texinfo documentation source. The goal is to produce a version of the RTEMS User's Guide in the specified mobile format along with instructions.

The goal of this task is to create a MOBI format version of the RTEMS Users Guide.

Details are at http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#eBook_Formats_for_RTEMS_Documentation

Title: Create RTEMS Project Wiki Page for ESA Exomars Mission
Description: The RTEMS Project has a number of flyers at http://www.rtems.org/flyers.html which provide some details on various projects which have used RTEMS.  Each of these flyers is based upon a Wiki page about that project with the same or similar text and pictures.  This task consists of preparing a wiki page on an RTEMS application which consists of approximately one to two pages of text plus 2 or more nice pictures or figures about the project and a few URLs of reference for more details.  The information on the flyers is based on this and is presented in a very uniform manner. The Wiki page is easier to edit and review collaboratively. We will create the flyer from the information on the Wiki page you create. Most of the information you need should be available from public sources on the Internet. When you take this task you may be given an email address of a contact for that project to obtain information from.  The wiki page you will create is for the ESA Exomars Mission. More details about this project and some hints for searching and creating content may be found at http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Info_for_flyers_for_various_projects_using_RTEMS

Title: Create Book Cover Template For RTEMS Documentation #1
Description:
Using an open source tool, create a book cover template that can be easily tailored for use with all RTEMS Documentation. This cover must be professional looking and follow the guidelines given at lulu.com for covers.

The template should have a suitable placeholder for variable information such as title, revision, publication date, etc.

The back cover should include at least a place for a paragraph or two description of the manual.

The RTEMS Project logo and URLs should be included.

Use RTEMS Project colors as much as possible while avoiding the cover looking garish. :)

Title: Create POSIX Timing Test psxtmcond02 (#0)
Description:
This task consists of creating the timing test testsuites/psxtmtests/psxtmcond02 for the POSIX API method when used in a particular manner. The test case is: pthread_cond_signal - no threads waiting.

If there is no dash in the description then this is the only case of interest for that method. If there are multiple methods then test both methods. The test should be created using the test instantiation helper and templates in rtems-testing/rtems-test-templates. This test will be using the template: psxtmtest_single.

See http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Add_a_POSIX_Timing_Test for more details

Title: Create RTEMS Project Wiki Page for Mitre Centaur Robot
Description: The RTEMS Project has a number of flyers at http://www.rtems.org/flyers.html which provide some details on various projects which have used RTEMS.  Each of these flyers is based upon a Wiki page about that project with the same or similar text and pictures.  This task consists of preparing a wiki page on an RTEMS application which consists of approximately one to two pages of text plus 2 or more nice pictures or figures about the project and a few URLs of reference for more details.  The information on the flyers is based on this and is presented in a very uniform manner. The Wiki page is easier to edit and review collaboratively. We will create the flyer from the information on the Wiki page you create. Most of the information you need should be available from public sources on the Internet. When you take this task you may be given an email address of a contact for that project to obtain information from.  The wiki page you will create is for the Mitre Centaur Robot. More details about this project and some hints for searching and creating content may be found at http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Info_for_flyers_for_various_projects_using_RTEMS

Title: Test Documentation Files update: tmtests/tmoverhd
Description:
This task consists of reading http://git.rtems.org/rtems/tree/testsuites/tmtests/tmoverhd/tmoverhd.doc and tmoverhd/testtask.c and edit tmoverhd.doc to describe the contents of tmoverhd/testtask.c in the correct format. Then submit the resulting tmoverhead to Google Doc.

Location of Test Documentation Files

These files are located in the testsuites folder http://git.rtems.org/rtems/tree/testsuites/ click in the folder and there should be a .doc which is the test document and a .scn which is the screen that should appear when the test is ran.

Format for Test Documentation Files

The correct format for the test documentation files is:

  1. If there is a copyright notice, please leave it intact
  2. Please use claim your work by adding your name and/or email
  3. "This file describes the directives and concepts tested by this test set."
  4. Test set name: name of the folder
  5. Directives: all the directives called in the test.c
  6. Concepts: describe what the test is doing -- it may help to look at the .scn which are the desired return values

Please see http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Test_Documentation_Files_update
for more details

Thanks!

Title: BSP Wiki Pages Info Boxes: ERC32 without FPU
Description:
RTEMS uses a Mediawiki installation for its wiki. Each embedded board supported by RTEMS is supposed to have its own wiki page. There is an Infobox on the upper right hand side of each BSP wiki page. Some BSPs do not have BSPs and even those that do have pages created do not always have a completed Infobox. This is necause we learned how to implement the Infoboxes after the pages were added, most of them are just stubs.

This task consists of finding the vendor specification on a particular board (which should be publicly available) and filling in the Infobox.

Please look at http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#BSP_Wiki_Pages_Info_Boxes for additional information.

Title: Identify new microprocessor architectures appropriate for RTEMS #1
Description:
Although most computer users are only familiar with the x86, PowerPC (Mac), and ARM (phones, etc.), there are at least a dozen other microprocessor architectures used in embedded systems. Identify one which RTEMS is not available for and determine if it is feasible to port RTEMS to it. If it is not feasible, identify why. If it is feasible, look at the features of the architecture that would be important to the person porting RTEMS to this architecture.

To get started, some ideas for architectures can be found at:http://gcc.gnu.org/viewcvs/trunk/libgcc/config/

Additional architectures can be found at: http://sourceware.org/cgi-bin/cvsweb.cgi/src/opcodes/?cvsroot=src and http://opencores.org/projects

If you know of an architecture that isn't on either list, please propose it anyway!

The expected result is a 1 paragraph to 1 page paper.

Title: Adapt an Eclipse Plug-In Module For Use In RTEMS Development
Description:
RTEMS is not a GUI application. Most RTEMS users only see a GUI when they are doing development. The most frequently used GUI development environment used by RTEMS developers is Eclipse. Take one of the Eclipse plugin modules identified as a research focused project and adapt it for use by the RTEMS community.

For more information:

http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Adapt_an_Eclipse_Plug-In_Module_For_Use_In_RTEMS_Development

** OR **

Another option would be to improve (add a feature), port (move to a new operating system) or update (make work with a recent version of RTEMS) an existing Eclipse Plug-in

http://www.rtems.com/ftp/pub/rtems/eclipse/updates/

http://wiki.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/RTEMS_Eclipse_Plug-in

Title: Identify Software Status: RTEMS ConfigKit
Description:
RTEMS Toolkits - We are defining collections of libraries and support programs which make it easier to get started for certain types of applications. Each potential component must be evaluated for license and appropriateness for use in an embedded environment like RTEMS. If the software is determined to have an appropriate license, written in a language that the RTEMS compiler supports, and doesn't have too many dependencies, we embed the software into RTEMS and the end user has functionality that is already documented and maintained. For example the RTEMS configuration kit enables an end-user to easily write a configuration parser that is well-documented.

The task consists of taking the proposed software package within the kit and determining the last date each package was modified. To complete this task submit a .txt (or edit the toolkit page directly) with the date the package was last modified.

The directions for this task can be found at: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Assess_New_Software

The URL for the config kit is: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/RTEMS_ConfigKit

Title: Identify Software Status: RTEMS Webkit
Description:
RTEMS Toolkits - We are defining collections of libraries and support programs which make it easier to get started for certain types of applications. Each potential component must be evaluated for license and appropriateness for use in an embedded environment like RTEMS. If the software is determined to have an appropriate license, written in a language that the RTEMS compiler supports, and doesn't have too many dependencies, we embed the software into RTEMS and the end user has functionality that is already documented and maintained. For example the RTEMS configuration kit enables an end-user to easily write a configuration parser that is well-documented.

The task consists of taking the proposed software package within the kit and determining the last date each package was modified.

Additionally, identify the license of thttpd and OpenLDAP.

To complete this task submit a .txt (or edit the toolkit page directly) with the date the package was last modified, and the identified licenses.

The directions for this task can be found at: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Assess_New_Software

The URL for the config kit is: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/RTEMS_WebKit

Title: Merged RSS Feed
Description:
According to Wikipedia, RSS Rich Site Summary (originally RDF Site Summary, often dubbed Really Simple Syndication) is a family of web feed formats used to publish frequently updated works—such as blog entries, news headlines, audio, and video—in a standardized format. Our example can be found at: http://www.rtems.com/wiki/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=rss

RSS allows users to avoid manually inspecting all of the websites they are interested in, and instead subscribe to websites such that all new content is pushed onto their browsers when it becomes available.

RTEMS is used by multiple applications that have their own RSS feeds. We would like to provide a single RSS feed for the set of applications using RTEMS.

Identify a tool that merges RSS feeds and use that to merge a few RSS feeds for us. We will want to make this available via our website.

http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Merged_RSS_Feed

Title: Identify new microprocessor architectures appropriate for RTEMS #2
Description:
Although most computer users are only familiar with the x86, PowerPC (Mac), and ARM (phones, etc.), there are at least a dozen other microprocessor architectures used in embedded systems. Identify one which RTEMS is not available for and determine if it is feasible to port RTEMS to it. If it is not feasible, identify why. If it is feasible, look at the features of the architecture that would be important to the person porting RTEMS to this architecture.

To get started, some ideas for architectures can be found at:http://gcc.gnu.org/viewcvs/trunk/libgcc/config/

Additional architectures can be found at: http://sourceware.org/cgi-bin/cvsweb.cgi/src/opcodes/?cvsroot=src and http://opencores.org/projects

Although RTEMS has been ported to Xilinx, other FPGA manufacturers can be found in: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field-programmable_gate_array#Major_manufacturers

If you know of an architecture that isn't on either list, please propose it anyway!

The expected result is a 1 paragraph to 1 page paper.

For additional information:

http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Identify_new_microprocessor_architectures_appropriate_for_RTEMS

Title: Identify Software Status: RTEMS Scriptkit
Description:
RTEMS Toolkits - We are defining collections of libraries and support programs which make it easier to get started for certain types of applications. Each potential component must be evaluated for license and appropriateness for use in an embedded environment like RTEMS. If the software is determined to have an appropriate license, written in a language that the RTEMS compiler supports, and doesn't have too many dependencies, we embed the software into RTEMS and the end user has functionality that is already documented and maintained. For example the RTEMS configuration kit enables an end-user to easily write a configuration parser that is well-documented.

The task consists of taking the proposed software package within the kit and determining the last date each package was modified. To complete this task submit a .txt (or edit the toolkit page directly) with the date the package was last modified.

The directions for this task can be found at: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Assess_New_Software

The URL for the config kit is: http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/RTEMS_ScriptKit

Title: Research New Software #1
Description:
RTEMS Toolkits - We are defining collections of libraries and support programs which make it easier to get started for certain types of applications. We haven't identified all potential toolkits or components. Please see above for toolkit areas identified so far.

This task consist of identifying an additional toolkit that would be beneficial for embedded systems development. To see what some other embedded systems developers are doing see: Buildroot Packages. To see how other major *nix-like distributors gather software, see: FreeBSD ports, Fedora packages, and Debian packages.

The deliverable is a .txt with a one paragraph explanation of the problem the kit addresses, and example software that would illustrate what type of software goes in the package (licensing would not be an issue at this stage of the proposal).

Title: Identify a Timeline Visualization Tool
Description:
RTEMS systems have the option to capture timestamped data about what is happening in the system. But reading long files with timestamped messages is not a good way to get insight into the run-time behavior of a system. Find us a free, open source timeline visualization tool which can be taught to read the RTEMS captured information.

Ideal solution would be one which dynamically updates as input arrives and is flexible on input sources (e.g. files, sockets, etc).

http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/GoogleCodeInProjects#Identify_a_Timeline_Visualization_Tool

Title: Create POSIX Timing Test psxspin01 (#12)
Description:
This task consists of creating the timing test testsuites/psxtmtests/ preempt for the POSIX API method when used in a particular manner. The test case is: pthread_spin_init - pthread_spin_destroy

If there is no dash in the description then this is the only case of interest for that method. If there are multiple methods then test both methods. The test should be created using the test instantiation helper and templates in rtems-testing/rtems-test-templates. This test will be using the template: psxtmtest_init_destroy

4. pthread_spin_trylock - not available

Title: Write Tasks for Next Year #2
Description:
The Google Code In student of 2012 did a lot of tasks this year, now we're thinking about what to do next year. This task consists of one (1) of the following:

a. writing out a task to be completed next year

- OR -

b. coming up with a short list of 5 possible task ideas

Try to keep the task simple and brief...

The http://www.rtems.org/wiki/index.php/Open_Projects is a good starting point for Google Code In tasks, so improving the associated wiki pages would be more in the scope of a GCI task than performing the open project. For example: identify the license, language, and last date a toolkit was maintained.

Title: Write a Fault Test Document
Description:
During the Google Code In we discovered there were problems with some of the tests, and we want to make a list of tests that are having issues.

To complete this task, write a document that captures information needed to reproduce the fault, and put it on ski-dive for other people working on the screen-shot tasks to fill in if they find faults in the tests.

The deliverable is a link to the document.
